A tropical wave becomes a depression when winds start swirling. The sun puts energy into the water, the top of the oceans and lowest part of the atmosphere. It is an exciting thing to watch. About one of six develop, said Clark. But the scientists do know what fuels a budding storm once development begins. When the depression that would become Gilbert neared Barbados, warm Atlantic waters nurtured it. We get 50 or 60 of these off Africa every summer. It reaches hurricane status when sustained winds hit 74 mph. By Sept 8, the system became a depression. 